# Human approval gates

## Rule
The `/implement` and `/bugfix` pipelines have **three mandatory, non-skippable** human approval gates:

- **Gate 1** — after the `planner-agent` produces its cross-repo plan, before any branches are created or code is written. Gate 1's reply also carries the per-repo base-branch choices (e.g., `approve; fb-rates-go=development, admin-backend=release/2026.04`), which feed directly into `base-branch-picker-agent`.
- **Review-Readiness Gate** — after `coder-agent` finishes writing the changes and **before** any review agent runs. The changes sit on the feature branch's working tree, **uncommitted and unstaged**. This gate hands control to the developer so they can read the diff, make their own edits, and only then green-light the reviews. The reviews run against whatever is in the working tree at the moment this gate is approved. `revise <notes>` re-runs `coder-agent` with the notes; `approve` starts the 14 review agents; `reject` halts.
- **Gate 2** — after **all 14 review agents have returned AND the orchestrator has posted the consolidated findings comment to the JIRA ticket**, before the pipeline terminates. Gate 2 MUST NOT prompt the developer until that JIRA comment has landed (see [jira-write-permissions](jira-write-permissions.md) for who posts and what is allowed). Approving Gate 2 ends the AI's work; the changes are still **uncommitted** on the feature branch, and the developer stages, commits, and pushes at their own convenience, then raises the MR.

The Review-Readiness Gate's prompt to the developer is fixed:

> Coding is complete on `<feature-branch>` — the changes are on your working tree, **uncommitted and unstaged**. Review them and make any edits you want. When you're ready, reply `approve` to start the 14 review agents / `revise <notes>` (coder-agent re-runs) / `reject`.

Gate 2's prompt to the developer is fixed:

> All 14 review agents have posted their findings as a consolidated comment on `<JIRA-KEY>`. Please review the JIRA comment first, then reply `approve` / `revise <notes>` / `reject`. On approve, the changes remain uncommitted — you stage, commit, and push them yourself.

Each gate accepts exactly one of three replies: `approve`, `reject`, or `revise <notes>`. Gate 1 additionally accepts per-repo base overrides in the same reply.

## Why
This is the 7-step meta-pattern used in every `freightify-web/.cursor/skills/**/SKILL.md`. The pipeline is authorized to think, search, and generate — but not to commit human-visible work without explicit approval.

## Constraints
- No "silent" gates; each gate emits a Checkpoint summarizing what was produced and what is about to happen.
- `revise <notes>` re-enters the current phase; it does not advance.
- `reject` halts the pipeline and preserves partial artifacts in `task-history/<KEY>.md`.
- Tools that run unattended (e.g., CI) must not impersonate a human at these gates; the developer's explicit reply is required.
- **Review-Readiness Gate ordering is mandatory**: no review agent may run until the developer has approved this gate. `coder-agent` finishes, leaves the changes uncommitted, and the orchestrator emits the Review-Readiness Gate prompt and waits. Fanning out to the review agents before this approval is a pipeline bug — the developer must be able to edit the code first.
- **Gate 2 ordering is mandatory**: the orchestrator MUST (a) wait for all 14 review agents to return, (b) aggregate their findings into one comment, (c) post that comment to the JIRA ticket via the allowed JIRA write path, and (d) only then emit the Gate 2 banner and prompt. Skipping any step is a pipeline bug — Gate 2 has nothing meaningful to approve without the reviewers' verdicts on JIRA.
- **The pipeline never stages, commits, or pushes.** No agent runs `git add`, `git commit`, or `git push` at any point. After Gate 2 approval the changes are still uncommitted; the developer owns staging/committing/pushing.
- **The pipeline never publishes the task-history either.** At Gate 2 it writes `<KEY>.md` with `published: false` and *reminds* (Step 13). The developer runs **`/publish-history`** when ready — which, in `<product>-ai-brain` only, branches off `development`, commits the record(s), and raises an MR (never merges; a separate agent merges). This is the single sanctioned git-write + MR automation, scoped to the brain repo's task-history `.md` — never service repos, never the developer's code.
- **Post-Gate-2 finalize is mandatory and non-skippable.** When the developer replies `approve` at Gate 2, the orchestrator MUST, in this order, before terminating:
  1. Call [`task-history-writer`](../skills/task-history-writer.md) with phase `gate-2` to append the final approval section to `<product>-ai-brain/task-history/<KEY>.md`.
  2. Verify the file exists at that exact path and that its frontmatter `last-phase: gate-2` is set. If the file is missing or the phase did not stamp, the orchestrator MUST NOT claim success — emit a halt banner per [`agent-attribution`](agent-attribution.md) (`### ▸ [12/12] task-history finalize` / `*HALT after Gate 2: finalize failed at <product>-ai-brain/task-history/<KEY>.md*`) and stop.
  3. Render the **completion panel** per [`pipeline-checklist`](pipeline-checklist.md) — the checklist table, the summary table (repo / branch / base / working-tree status `uncommitted` / files / review result / JIRA comment id / task-history path), and next steps (the developer stages, commits, and pushes: `git add <files>` → `git commit` → `git push origin <feature-branch>`, then opens the MR). The panel ALSO shows the **task-history publish reminder (Step 13)**: `<KEY>.md` was written with `published: false`, and the panel lists every still-pending record (`published: false`) with — *"📌 Push pending — run `/publish-history` to branch off `development` and raise an MR: `<file names>`."* The pipeline itself NEVER pushes the record; publishing is developer-triggered.
  4. Only then end the run.
- On Gate 2 `reject` or `revise`, the orchestrator still calls `task-history-writer` (with phase `halted` for reject, or repeating the current phase for revise) so the task-history file always reflects reality.
- Each gate emits its banner per [agent-attribution](agent-attribution.md) (`▸ Gate 1 — ...` / `▸ Review-Readiness Gate — ...` / `▸ Gate 2 — ...`).

## Examples

### Good
> Gate 1 emitted after planner-agent. Developer replies `revise: also update the admin-backend lookup table`. Planner re-runs with that constraint.

### Bad
> Coder-agent starts writing code after planner-agent without any Gate 1 reply because the test harness auto-approved.

